snippet.title: How Does Ketamine Work?
snippet.description:
Ketamine is a Horse Tranquilizer, but it is also a psychedelic and hallucinogenic recreational drug. Is Ketamine Safe? Is Ketamine Dangerous? Can Ketamine be used to treat depression?

Studies looking at Ketamine as an antidepressant have shown that this sedative can reduce symptoms of anxiety and depression, although the safety and side effects of this treatment are still being investigated. 

Ketamine, also known as Ket, Special K, Ket, KitKat and Donkey Dust, is a tranquilizer that is normally used by vets for sedation and pain reduction, but when used as a recreational drug, it can have a variety of effects on your brain, your body and your health.

This video discusses the pharmacology of Ketamine including it’s mechanism of action as a dissociative anaesthetic as well as an antidepressant. We also discuss Ketamine overdose and the K Hole, what to do in this situation. Finally, we look at the concept of using ketamine for depression.

7 SCIENTIFIC STRATEGIES TO LIVE HAPPIER AND HEALTHIER EVERY DAY

snippet.textDisplay: I have treatment-resistant agitated depression/debilitating anxiety/pure ocd/adhd and I’ve taken over 80+ meds over the yrs, few of which have worked for me, & when they did it was marginal at best. I experience suicidal ideation most of the time & ketamine has been the ONLY thing that is helping me feel like I’m not stuck in hell. It’s pretty miraculous imo; I’m going for my 5th infusion tomorrow (usually it’s 6 infusions over 2 weeks) actually. The disassociative/“trip” experience for me is both profoundly spiritual and psychedelic, yet also gets unsettling at times, depending on my state of mind before it starts. I literally feel as if I’m not a singular being, it’s as if the ketamine rockets you into some divine cosmos & you feel a “connection” w all of humanity, you feel that love is all that matters - or rather you have this realization - it’s overwhelming & hard to explain! Some of the imagery is beyond fantastic...sorry this comment is getting long! Point is, it’s not a magic bullet, nor cure, but for me it’s the only thing that helps me feel like life is worth living again - while it lasts (usually a few months). The tragic part is that insurance doesn’t cover it, it’s very expensive :(

snippet.title: The Travelling Scientist
snippet.description:
Hey there, I’m Jesse Crowe, The Travelling Scientist. I’m an adventurous nerd who travels around the world, meeting with scientists and doctors to discuss the latest research surrounding medicine, health and wellbeing.

Today, drugs, vitamins and supplements are being used more frequently than ever before! With technology advancing rapidly and our health being so important to us, I believe that it is crucial to understand exactly what we are putting into our bodies!

Therefore, I am committed to researching and sharing the latest discoveries regarding the medicines that we are prescribed to consume so that you can feel informed and comfortable when you take any sort of drug, vitamin or supplement!

caption.text: Ketamine...What's the deal???
Today, we're going to be looking at the drug Ketamine, answering three key questions
1.How does Ketamine work?
2.What are the dangers of using Ketamine?
3.What are the potential benefits of using Ketamine?

Hey there guys, I'm Jesse Crowe, The
Travelling Scientist
and after studying years of pharmacology, I'm here to help you live smarter, healthier and happier lives!
Now, Ketamine, also known as K, Ket, KitKat
Vitamin K, Special K, Super k, Donkey Dust...
...and even horse tranquilizer
because this drug is mainly used by vets when they're doing surgery on dogs, cats, and even horses
But what is Ketamine and why am I telling you about it?
Well, Ketamine is a dissociative anaesthetic
Meaning that it causes a feeling of separation from your environment, and also separation from your body
And the reason I'm telling you about Ketamine
is because it can also be used as a recreational drug
At low doses, Ketamine can cause a feeling of mind and body separation
Seeing trails
A sense of floating and numbness
Blurred vision
And even hallucinations!
When Ketamine is taken in higher doses
It can make your legs feel very weak and wobbly
It can make your heart race
It can make breathing...really difficult...
And you can also fall into a K hole
Where you sort of have an out of body experience
And you can be floating through space or experiencing all of eternity at a single point in time
But a K hole can also lead to a near death experience
Where you feel completely powerless and totally confused...which sounds terrifying!
*shakes it off*
So how DOES Ketamine actually work?
Ketamine is an antagonist of NDMA receptors which are found in nerve cells
and NDMA receptors allow the nerve cells to transmit signals
so by antagonising these receptors, Ketamine reduces the amount of signalling throughout the body
Thereby reducing pain levels, reducing muscle control and reducing brain signalling in general
And the effects of Ketamine last for around an hour or so, depending on how much you take
Ketamine is a horse tranquilizer!
It is not the kind of thing we should be putting into our bodies for fun...
But I know what your crazy kids get up to nowadays
And so if you were to, say, accidentally ingest some Ketamine
Here are the kind of dangers that you might want to look out for...
Injury! When you're on Ketamine, you can't feel pain
And you're probably being really clumsy, so you could potentially injure yourself
Really badly, without even realising
Vulnerability! As you lose control of your muscles
And your mind loses its hold on reality
You put yourself in a really vulnerable position to be hurt or taken advantage of by others
So be really mindful of that!
Looking long-term, if you use Ketamine often
Side effects can include: Stomach pain, Kidney problems and Bladder damage
This is because Ketamine is toxic
It really damages our organs as it passes through the body
And it's excreted through the urine, so it sits in the bladder for quite a while
Causing ulceration, inflammation and scarring
Which can lead to Bladder shrinkage, Incontinence, and worst of all...
...Bloody Urine...ewww
So if you care about your private parts at all, and I know you do!
Please DON'T use Ketamine long term
you will RUIN your junk
That being said, there are no physical withdrawal symptoms for Ketamine
So it's not really an addictive drug, but some people can become reliant on it
With a sort of psychological dependence
And you do start to become more tolerant of Ketamine
Meaning you need a higher dose each time to get that same dissociative effect
And as you take more Ketamine, you increase your risk of overdose...
An overdose on pure Ketamine is pretty rare...
You would need to consume a lot!
BUT, if you have a friend on Ketamine who starts vomiting or seizing
or becomes unconscious or paralysed
Then call an ambulance immediately!
They can come quickly and help take care of your friend and help them to recover safely
Don't worry about the fact that you're using an illicit substance, that's not important!
You need to help save your friend's life!
Research is currently being conducted to determine
whether Ketamine can be used for treatment resistant depression
That is, depression that is unaffected by 2 or more different antidepressants
Ketamine administered BY doctors TO patients
Has been shown to have a rapid antidepressant effect that can last for several days
And researchers believe that this is because the Ketamine is promoting a complex signalling cascade
Which is resulting in more synapses and increased neuronal connectivity
Particularly in the Prefrontal Cortex of the brain
However, there are no long-term studies looking at the safety and efficacy of Ketamine as an Antidepressant
You need to remember that there are risks when taking this drug
And by no means should you be using Ketamine to treat your own depression!
You SHOULD talk to your doctor about getting an appropriate treatment
And if you want to do something right now...
You can download my FREE E-book
"Seven Scientific Strategies to help you live a Happier and Healthier Life"
Anyway, that's all for today guys, thank you so much for watching
If you learned something in this video, click the Like button down below
And let me know what you think about Ketamine in the Comments section down below
You can also Share this video with anyone you know who has tried Ketamine
Or anyone who is worried about your usage of Ketamine
And finally, next week's video is going to be all about Anxiety, living with it
And how to manage Anxiety
So make sure you Subscribe for more Travelling Science every single week
And I'll see you guys next Science Sunday
Cheers!
